00:15:11,633 --> 00:15:14,533
This was not a natural disaster, but a

157
00:15:14,900 --> 00:15:16,200
man-made, systemic catastrophe—the inevitable consequence of expert knowledge attempting to replace practical wisdom. Scott introduces two ancient Greek concepts in his book, which form the core of his analytical framework: one is Techne,

158
00:15:30,166 --> 00:15:31,766
technical knowledge—knowledge that can be coded, taught, and standardized, such as knowledge in agricultural textbooks, soil pH, nitrogen, phosphorus, and potassium ratios, and pest and disease control plans. The other is Metis, practical wisdom—situational, experiential,

159
00:15:36,300 --> 00:15:38,200
and ineffable knowledge, such as an old farmer's judgment in a specific situation: whether to water more this year, or whether this land is suitable for planting corn.

160
00:15:40,400 --> 00:15:42,333
A core assumption of modernity is that Techne can replace Metis; as long as we scientize and standardize knowledge, we no longer need those empiricist elements. Scott argues that this is a fundamental mistake. It's not that Techne is unimportant, but rather that it cannot replace Metis. An agricultural

161
00:15:57,333 --> 00:16:00,333
PhD might know all the theories of soil science, but if he hasn't actually farmed, his knowledge is

